Question 2a

num.of.samples <- 100000
p.values <- numeric(num.of.samples) 
 
for (i in seq_len(num.of.samples)) { 
  # Step 1: Simulate observed data x_1,...,x_100 ~ N(0,1) under H0 
  n <- 100 
  mu <- 0 
  sigma <- 1 
  x <- rnorm(n = n, mean = mu, sd = sigma) 
  # Step 2: Compute p-value of one-sample two-sided t-test H0: mu = 0 
  p.values[i] <- t.test(x, mu = 0, paired = FALSE, alternative = 'two.sided')$p.value 
} 
 
hist(p.values, breaks = 100)

cat("It does look like Unif(0,1) distribution")

Question 3a

alpha <- 0.05 # Fix significance level to control type I error 
 
num.of.samples <- 100000
reject.H0 <- logical(num.of.samples) 

for (i in seq_len(num.of.samples)) { 
  # Step 1: Simulate observed data x_1,...,x_n ~ N(mu1,sigma) under H1 1 = 0.6
  n <- 10 
  mu1 <- 0.6 
  sigma <- 1 
  x <- rnorm(n = n, mean = mu1, sd = sigma) 
  # Step 2: Perform one-sample one-sided t-test H0: mu = 0 
  p.value <- t.test(x, mu = 0, paired = FALSE, alternative = 'greater')$p.value 
  # print(p.value[i])
  # Step 3: TRUE if reject H0 based on comparing p-value vs alpha 
  reject.H0[i] <- (p.value <  alpha)
  # print(reject.H0[i])
} 
# reject.H0
mean(reject.H0) # Power of test = 1 - beta, percent of true
## [1] 0.54191
cat("The power of the test when 1 = 0.6 is", mean(reject.H0))
## The power of the test when 1 = 0.6 is 0.54191

alpha <- 0.05 # Fix significance level to control type I error 
 
num.of.samples <- 100000
reject.H0 <- logical(num.of.samples) 
for (i in seq_len(num.of.samples)) { 
  # Step 1: Simulate observed data x_1,...,x_n ~ N(mu1,sigma) under H1 1 = 0.6
  n <- 10 
  mu1 <- 0.8
  sigma <- 1 
  x <- rnorm(n = n, mean = mu1, sd = sigma) 
  # Step 2: Perform one-sample one-sided t-test H0: mu = 0 
  p.value <- t.test(x, mu = 0, paired = FALSE, alternative = 'greater')$p.value 
  # print(p.value[i])
  # Step 3: TRUE if reject H0 based on comparing p-value vs alpha 
  reject.H0[i] <- (p.value <  alpha)
  # print(reject.H0[i])
} 
# reject.H0
mean(reject.H0) # Power of test = 1 - beta, percent of true
## [1] 0.75765
cat("The power of the test when 1 = 0.8 is", mean(reject.H0), "\n")
## The power of the test when 1 = 0.8 is 0.75765
cat("The power is higher when 1 = 0.8 compared to 1 = 0.6")
## The power is higher when 1 = 0.8 compared to 1 = 0.6

Question 3c

alpha <- 0.05 # Fix significance level to control type I error 
 
num.of.samples <- 100000
reject.H0 <- logical(num.of.samples) 
for (i in seq_len(num.of.samples)) { 
  # Step 1: Simulate observed data x_1,...,x_n ~ N(mu1,sigma) under H1 1 = 0.6
  n <- 20
  mu1 <- 0.6 
  sigma <- 1 
  x <- rnorm(n = n, mean = mu1, sd = sigma) 
  # Step 2: Perform one-sample one-sided t-test H0: mu = 0 
  p.value <- t.test(x, mu = 0, paired = FALSE, alternative = 'greater')$p.value 
  # print(p.value[i])
  # Step 3: TRUE if reject H0 based on comparing p-value vs alpha 
  reject.H0[i] <- (p.value <  alpha)
  # print(reject.H0[i])
} 
# reject.H0
mean(reject.H0) # Power of test = 1 - beta, percent of true
## [1] 0.82837
cat("The power of the test when 1 = 0.6 and n = 20 is", mean(reject.H0), "\n")
## The power of the test when 1 = 0.6 and n = 20 is 0.82837
cat("Power from 3a is around 0.5 when 1 = 0.6 and n = 10. So, if the sample size  increases, then more observed data would allow us to detect 1 more easily.")
## Power from 3a is around 0.5 when 1 = 0.6 and n = 10. So, if the sample size  increases, then more observed data would allow us to detect 1 more easily.

Question 4a

num.of.repeat <- 10 
p.values <- numeric(num.of.repeat) 
for (i in seq_len(num.of.repeat)) { 
  # Step 1: Simulate observed data x_1,...,x_n ~ Bern(p1) under H1 
  n <- 1e5 
  # n <- 10^11
  p1 <- 0.5 + 1e-5 
  x <- rbinom(n = 1, size = n, prob = p1) # Find 1 random value from a sample of n with probability of p1.
  # Step 2: Compute p-value of two-sided binomial proportion test H0: p = 0.5 
  p.values[i] <- prop.test(sum(x), n, p = 0.5, alternative = 'two.sided', correct = FALSE)$p.value 
}

Question 4b

for (k in seq(5, 1000, by=1)) {
  num.of.repeat <- 10 
  p.values <- numeric(num.of.repeat) 
  for (i in seq_len(num.of.repeat)) { 
    # Step 1: Simulate observed data x_1,...,x_n ~ Bern(p1) under H1 
    n <- 10^k 
    p1 <- 0.5 + 1e-5 
    x <- rbinom(n = 1, size = n, prob = p1) # Find 1 random value from a sample of n with probability of p1.
    # Step 2: Compute p-value of two-sided binomial proportion test H0: p = 0.5 
    p.values[i] <- prop.test(sum(x), n, p = 0.5, alternative = 'two.sided', correct = FALSE)$p.value 
  } 
  p.values
  max(p.values)
  cat("The max p.values is", max(p.values), "\n")
  if (max(p.values) < 0.01) {
    cat("k needs to be", k, "when n is increasing exponentially for the max p.values < 0.01")
    break
  }
  print(k)
}
